      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial FEA solver (Ansys) with documented QA procedures; FDA in-house scripts under version control with unit tests.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2021 R2 is a commercially validated solver with ISO 9001 QA documentation. FDA in-house pre/post-processing scripts are maintained under Git version control with peer-reviewed unit tests. Achieved level meets required level for Medium model risk."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions solved to within 1% relative error for linear elastic beam bending.",
      "rationale": "The FEA solver was exercised against Timoshenko beam bending benchmarks and patch tests for hexahedral and tetrahedral elements. All benchmark residuals were below 0.8%, satisfying the 1% criterion. Code verification is consistent with Gradation 2 for the declared model risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change <2% between medium and fine mesh; GCI reported.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was performed on the pedicle screw shank and rod interface regions. The Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for stiffness QoI was 1.3%, below the 2% threshold. The production mesh (approx. 420k elements) was selected at the medium-to-fine transition where incremental QoI change was 0.9%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual force norm <1e-5 at convergence; energy balance checked for each load step.",
      "rationale": "All nonlinear load step solutions converged with a residual force norm below 1e-6. Energy balance was verified at each of the 20 load increments. No spurious zero-energy modes were detected. Solver error contribution to total QoI uncertainty is estimated at <0.3%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent analyst review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments completed with no critical discrepancies.",
      "rationale": "An independent FDA analyst performed a blind review of model setup files, boundary condition definitions, and material property assignments. Two minor documentation gaps were identified and corrected prior to final analysis runs. No critical use errors were found. Simulation log files are archived and traceable to the final result set."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum linear elastic model with nonlinear contact at screw-rod and rod-block interfaces; material isotropy assumption justified by titanium alloy microstructure data.",
      "rationale": "The model employs continuum linear elasticity for screw and rod bodies (Ti-6Al-4V, isotropic) with augmented Lagrangian contact at all interfaces. Anisotropy of the UHMWPE vertebral body blocks is addressed by sensitivity analysis showing <4% QoI sensitivity to ±20% modulus variation. Model form is consistent with prior FDA validation studies for metallic spinal implants."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from MMPDS-11 and supplier certificates of conformance; geometric dimensions from CMM inspection of test articles.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa) and yield strength (880 MPa) are taken from MMPDS-11 with lot-specific CoC values within ±3%. UHMWPE block modulus was measured by DMA on five representative specimens (mean 1.02 GPa, CV 4.1%). Screw and rod geometry was verified by CMM inspection of three production-lot samples; nominal CAD dimensions agreed within 0.05 mm."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 constructs from production lots tested; lot traceability documented; no outliers excluded without cause.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs were assembled from two production lots (6 and 5 units) spanning two independent laboratories. Lot traceability is fully documented. One construct exhibited anomalous stiffness (>3 SD from mean) and was retained in the analysis after investigation confirmed a polyaxial head seating anomaly; its inclusion is conservative. Sample size exceeds the N=10 minimum for the declared consequence level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions replicate COU loading environment; multiple load levels or configurations tested.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration (6° offset, 10 mm/min crosshead speed) at ambient temperature. Only one load configuration was evaluated, which does not fully replicate the multi-directional in vivo loading environment. This factor is below the required level (2 vs. 3); the shortfall is acknowledged and accepted by the credibility assessment team given the regulatory precedent for F1717 as the standard acceptance test for spinal implants."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model inputs for validation simulations match measured experimental inputs within stated uncertainty bounds; no free parameters adjusted post-hoc.",
      "rationale": "All model inputs for the validation simulations were locked prior to experimental data unblinding. Material properties, geometry, boundary conditions, and contact parameters were set from pre-test characterization data. No parameter tuning was performed after experimental results were received. Input equivalency was confirmed by a traceability matrix mapping each model parameter to its experimental measurement source."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All QoIs satisfy <10% mean difference criterion and E/uval < 1.96 for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "Mean percent differences for the three QoIs: stiffness 4.2%, yield force 6.8%, force at 40 mm 5.1% — all below the 10% acceptance threshold. E/uval ratios were 0.87, 1.31, and 1.02 respectively, all below 1.96. The validation comparison metric satisfies pre-established acceptance criteria across both laboratories and all three QoIs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs are directly linked to the COU decision (construct mechanical performance); clinical relevance of each QoI is documented.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and directly characterize the mechanical performance relevant to the 510(k) submission. Each QoI maps to a distinct failure mode: stiffness to subsidence risk, yield force to fatigue life estimation, and force at 40 mm to catastrophic failure margin. Clinical relevance is documented in the predicate device comparison."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation geometry, loading, and boundary conditions are representative of the COU; any differences are bounded by sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "The validation constructs use the identical screw design, rod diameter, and UHMWPE block geometry as the COU device. The F1717 test fixture replicates the primary in vivo loading mode (compression-bending) with documented biomechanical justification. Differences between the bench model and in vivo conditions (e.g., absence of bone ingrowth) are addressed by sensitivity analysis confirming these factors contribute <5% to QoI uncertainty."
    }
